embedfield:
Update mongo document as a whole or specific fields

Scenario

I have a conversation document in mongodb , I have to add messages to a messages array and update the last sent date , see schema below.

{ 
"_id" : NumberInt(5), 
"CurrentOwnerId" : NumberInt(9), 
"LastSent" : ISODate("2019-06-21T11:57:32.861+0000"), 
"Messages" : [
    {
        "_id" : BinData(3, "nuC1iYTKtkGzSuv7pVHsKg=="), 
        "MessageContent" : "Hi There", 
        "Status" : "Pending", 
        "DateSent" : ISODate("2019-06-21T11:57:32.861+0000"), 
        "Method" : "Slack"
    }
 ]
}

My question

Would it be more efficient to simply read out the whole document (using the BsonId) and update the document via c# as a whole ie pushing my message to the array and setting the last sent day and then updating the document as a whole using the driver OR do two calls to the database using $set and $push operators to achieve what I want to do.
answer: `the order of the properties needs to be param=list or grid before the default orderid for my script to work correctly` This isn't the case at all. The `getParametersByName` function is designed to retrieve the properties from the URL by name, not by position. The order makes no difference.

The best way to use mongodb, redis and rabbit mq through karatedsl?

Is there the best way for me to use mongodb, redis and rabbitmq through karatedsl ? or i have to write my own java code for them all ?
answer: This is misleading. Clustered table and partitioned table are not true table types. Both are heap or index organized. Partitioned table just have multiple data segments. And tables within indexed cluster are still heap tables, they just share the cluster's index. And there can be more than two tables in a cluster so there can be rows from more than two tables in a single block.

answer: Also note that deadlock detection is your friend.  The deadlock error is telling you that the two transactions are intermingling their row/index locks in such a way that one of them is not likely to succeed, and had the deadlock not been detected, they would have waited forever for each other, blocking on incompatible locks.  The transaction that has made the least progress in terms of rows locked when the deadlock is detected will be killed, and needs to be retried, at which point you will hit the integrity constraint error.
